1
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:10,700
I could be happy with you

2
00:00:11,700 --> 00:00:15,415
If you could be happy with me

3
00:00:15,900 --> 00:00:18,100
I'd be contented

4
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:20,253
Here, Pol.

6
00:00:22,800-> 00:00:23,724
Here.

5
00:00:24,358 --> 00:00:25,192
What about my money?

6
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:28,461
-Where's my baby?
-She's over there!

7
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:30,190
Put it on the slate!

8
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,900
I'll get the sack
if they're late again.

9
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:37,300
Hurry up, then.

10
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:39,200
Just along there.

11
00:00:47,447 --> 00:00:48,649
Good afternoon,
Mr. and Mrs. Parkhill.

12
00:00:48,900 --> 00:00:49,600
Good afternoon, Len.

13
00:00:49,700 --> 00:00:51,160
All for Mrs. P,
I'm afraid.

14
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:53,754
-Must be bills, then.
-Thank you, darling.

15
00:00:54,655 --> 00:00:56,456
My man sent me
maintenance order, Len?

16
00:00:56,456 --> 00:00:57,658
I'll have a look now.

17
00:00:58,125 --> 00:01:01,328
Old gin, old pals
and jolly good company

18
00:01:02,062 --> 00:01:03,296
Disgusting!

19
00:01:03,296 --> 00:01:04,665
For you, dear.

20
00:01:04,665 --> 00:01:05,900
Are you selling by post now, love?

21
00:01:05,900 --> 00:01:06,667
__

22
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:08,060
Hi there, gorgeous.

23
00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:10,860
I suppose I should be thankful
for small mercies.

24
00:01:10,900 --> 00:01:12,760
-Anything?
-Nothing for you this morning.

25
00:01:12,800 --> 00:01:13,800
They are all in yet, Len?

26
00:01:13,900 --> 00:01:15,200
All in except Rita and Tommy.

27
00:01:15,400 --> 00:01:18,200
Oh, he won't be long.
You can hear him coming a mile off.

28
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:21,760
Practising, practising.
Don't you ever stop dancing?

29
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:24,400
Hey, toots. I'm in training
for my second big break.

30
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:26,500
You're kidding.
What was the first?

31
00:01:26,600 --> 00:01:28,822
Didn't you ever hear
of the baby toast of Broadway?

32
00:01:29,423 --> 00:01:30,824
Tiny Tom, the tapping tot?

33
00:01:35,796 --> 00:01:37,200
Grew up, didn't you?

34
00:01:37,300 --> 00:01:38,699
Overnight.

35
00:01:38,699 --> 00:01:42,060
And who can use a Tiny Tod
who's 10 feet tall?

36
00:01:42,100 --> 00:01:43,437
How about Barnum and Bailey?

37
00:01:44,900 --> 00:01:48,560
They already had one
and he was a bearded lady.

38
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:51,900
So I booked a one-way ticket
on a cattle boat to merry old England.

39
00:01:52,100 --> 00:01:54,160
Blimey!
From Broadway to Portsmouth?

40
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:57,300
-There's a comedown in it.
-A stepping-stone, toots.

41
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:00,087
A mere stepping-stone to stardom.

42
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:06,400
Not bad!

43
00:02:09,730 --> 00:02:12,400
-Here's your stuff, love.
-Ta.

44
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,000
Cheese and chutney, right?

45
00:02:14,100 --> 00:02:15,600
Thanks, Pol. Put it on the slate.

46
00:02:15,700 --> 00:02:17,000
All right.

47
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:21,141
Ta.

48
00:02:26,379 --> 00:02:27,447
Who sent me the flowers?

49
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:32,119
I forget.

50
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,200
I bought one apple too many.
Would you like it?

51
00:02:37,100 --> 00:02:37,891
No, thanks.

52
00:02:39,700 --> 00:02:40,800
I've had one already.

53
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:49,936
Pol,

54
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:51,571
I'll have it if it's going begging.

55
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:54,000
All right, love.
You have it.

56
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:54,900
Ta.

57
00:02:55,400 --> 00:02:56,510
Five minutes, everyone.

58
00:03:07,100 --> 00:03:08,789
Afternoon. Here is your gin.

59
00:03:08,789 --> 00:03:10,900
Don't you knock when
you enter the star's dressing room?

60
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:11,660
Sorry.

61
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:14,094
They didn't have smoked salmon
so I got salmon shrimp, all right?

62
00:03:14,094 --> 00:03:17,160
Paste? Sure you don't expect
Mrs. P. to eat paste, do you?

63
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:19,500
I'm sorry, but it was
the nearest they had.

64
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:23,200
Nearest they had! Look at that!
Take them away.

65
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:27,060
Never mind, Polly. I just need
something to settle me before I go on.

66
00:03:27,100 --> 00:03:28,560
Anything will do.

67
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:30,243
But it was the best I had, Mrs. P.

68
00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:32,900
Ship them by appointment.
They have it at Buckingham Palace.

69
00:03:33,100 --> 00:03:35,160
When they're entertaining
their Cockney Highnesses.

70
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:37,360
The pearly King
and Queen, I suppose.

71
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:39,300
-How long we've got?
-Five minutes.

72
00:03:39,419 --> 00:03:40,353
And my change?

73
00:03:41,621 --> 00:03:43,290
I owe you 2 and 11 pence
with 3 farthings.

74
00:03:43,290 --> 00:03:45,500
If I give you a farthing
you can give me 3 bob.

75
00:03:48,900 --> 00:03:49,700
Polly!

76
00:03:52,365 --> 00:03:53,600
Ta, Mrs. P.
You shouldn't.

77
00:03:56,300 --> 00:03:57,600
The way you encourage her!

78
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:02,100
Overture and beginners, please.

79
00:04:04,100 --> 00:04:06,060
My hatbox came undone last day, Polly.

80
00:04:06,100 --> 00:04:08,114
It won't happen again, Ms. Maisie.

81
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:09,900
Help me with my hooks.

82
00:04:12,219 --> 00:04:15,160
I do love my feather duster
on the upside of my dismal, Polly.

83
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:16,656
Do try and remember.

84
00:04:16,900 --> 00:04:18,600
Got a fag, Pol?

85
00:04:19,200 --> 00:04:20,700
Only a Woodbine.

86
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:26,166
Ain't he lovely?

87
00:04:29,102 --> 00:04:31,800
Polly, don't whistle
in the dressing room.

88
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:33,773
-Why not?
-Because it's unlucky.

89
00:04:33,974 --> 00:04:36,800
Now go outside, turn around three times
and knock on the door.

90
00:04:38,345 --> 00:04:41,882
-What do nursing mothers need?
-Virol.

91
00:04:43,900 --> 00:04:44,900
Come in.

92
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:47,000
-Now swear.
-Damn.

93
00:04:47,300 --> 00:04:49,900
-Where is that lazy lady?
-She'll turn up, don't worry.

94
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
She'll be late
to her own funeral, that one.

95
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:54,500
Where is Rita?

96
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:57,700
Isn't she here yet?
I don't expect she'll be missed.

97
00:04:57,800 --> 00:04:59,700
She is the star of the show.

98
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:04,170
Do you really think so?

99
00:05:05,900 --> 00:05:07,600
She'll be fined again
if she ain't careful.

100
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,100
They're all called, Mr. Max.
Except Rita. She ain't here yet.

101
00:05:52,300 --> 00:05:54,900
Not here?
Put her down for a fine.

102
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:57,600
If you fine her again
she will owe you money.

103
00:05:58,200 --> 00:05:59,600
With this house I need it.

104
00:06:00,200 --> 00:06:04,500
Why must these wretched garden fêtes
always coincide with our matinees?

105
00:06:04,900 --> 00:06:08,260
And not a cloud in the sky.
Let me know the minute she arrives.

106
00:06:08,300 --> 00:06:09,169
Yes, Mr. Max

107
00:06:27,900 --> 00:06:30,800
Blimey! There's more on stage
than in the blooming audience.

108
00:06:36,900 --> 00:06:37,730
Down there.

109
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:09,000
Is that Gaston, the costumier?

110
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:12,900
It is Madame Dubonnet's maid.

111
00:07:13,700 --> 00:07:15,101
Dubonnet.

112
00:07:23,343 --> 00:07:25,278
Mme Dubonnet de Villa Caprice.

113
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:26,300
Accent!

114
00:07:26,400 --> 00:07:28,000
Accent!

115
00:07:31,900 --> 00:07:34,400
The school for young ladies.

116
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:40,760
I wish to know if you have ready
the costume for Ms. Polly Browne.

117
00:07:46,166 --> 00:07:47,133
Accent.

118
00:07:48,301 --> 00:07:51,604
She wishes it for
the carnival ball "ce soir".

119
00:07:53,273 --> 00:07:56,476
You do not comprehend?
Then get me Monsieur Gaston himself.

120
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:07,560
She's no more French than I am.

121
00:08:07,600 --> 00:08:10,060
-Rita here?
-No, Mr. Max. Naughty!

122
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:11,191
Nobody asked for your opinion.

123
00:08:11,191 --> 00:08:14,160
She was out having an ice tea
with a sailor around lunch time.

124
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:16,096
Opening time, dear.
Let's be honest.

125
00:08:16,096 --> 00:08:17,330
Fine publicity.

126
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:19,833
-She's never missed an entrance yet.
-Mind your hatbox, Dulcie.

127
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,260
She's never been sane
since I turned her into a star.
It went to her head totally.

128
00:08:27,300 --> 00:08:29,200
-Telephone, Mr. Max.
-Tell them to ring again.

129
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:31,360
How can you expect me to speak
at a time like this!

130
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:33,300
They must speak to you
personally!

131
00:08:33,800 --> 00:08:35,900
It's not C. B. Cochrane
from London, is it?

132
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:38,184
No. It's the hospital.

133
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:42,122
Then you deliver it right away?

134
00:08:49,896 --> 00:08:52,200
Have you forgotten who you are?

135
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:54,667
Forgotten who we are?

136
00:08:55,100 --> 00:08:56,900
Of course not!

137
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:02,660
We are perfect
young ladies

138
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:07,780
preparing to take
our places among the noblesse

139
00:09:08,100 --> 00:09:11,260
We are perfect young ladies
Preparing to make

140
00:09:11,300 --> 00:09:14,954
the most of the charm
we possess

141
00:09:14,954 --> 00:09:18,525
You're being finished
And your families' wealth

142
00:09:18,525 --> 00:09:20,560
may be diminished

143
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:25,532
But at least you all
have perfect health

144
00:09:27,300 --> 00:09:30,900
And making the grade
is our duty, you see

145
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:34,260
For perfect young ladies are we

146
00:09:34,300 --> 00:09:36,660
We are perfect young ladies

147
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:41,447
We hope to attract
a husband whose credit is good

148
00:09:42,182 --> 00:09:43,560
You're maybe young ladies

149
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:45,660
But why don't you act

150
00:09:45,700 --> 00:09:48,600
The way that a young lady should?

151
00:09:48,800 --> 00:09:52,560
-I've often told you
-Please don't tell us again

152
00:09:52,600 --> 00:09:55,460
-I ought to scold you
-But

153
00:09:55,500 --> 00:09:57,560
you know it would be
quite in vain

154
00:09:57,600 --> 00:10:01,260
For being our maid is
your duty, you see

155
00:10:01,300 --> 00:10:04,900
For perfect young ladies are we

156
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:57,690
Terrible, terrible.

157
00:10:58,491 --> 00:10:59,559
Not Rita.

158
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:03,263
Trapped her high heel
in the tram line. A foot.

159
00:11:03,263 --> 00:11:04,564
It ain't off?

160
00:11:04,998 --> 00:11:08,160
Of course not. Mild fracture.
But she's laid up just the same.

161
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:09,560
We're ruined.

162
00:11:10,300 --> 00:11:12,472
No, we're not.
You will have to go on.

163
00:11:12,472 --> 00:11:13,473
Get ready.

164
00:11:13,900 --> 00:11:16,760
What, me?
But I'm only the A. S. M.

165
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:18,160
I can't go on.

166
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:21,440
It's the assistant stage manager's job
to understudy everybody's part.

167
00:11:21,480 --> 00:11:23,160
Now, I told you that
when I took you on.

168
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:24,700
Now, hurry up
and don't argue.

169
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,700
You've got exactly 5 minutes.

170
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:28,900
I do not feel funny.

171
00:12:12,500 --> 00:12:14,133
I want the best seat
in the house.

172
00:12:14,900 --> 00:12:15,568
Let me see.

173
00:12:17,900 --> 00:12:19,800
You could have the royal box.

174
00:12:20,200 --> 00:12:21,140
I'll take it.

175
00:12:22,742 --> 00:12:27,347
Except that it's permanently reserved
for the princess Arthur of Connaught.

176
00:12:27,800 --> 00:12:29,349
We often stay with her.

177
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:33,000
Oh, really!

178
00:12:34,500 --> 00:12:36,356
How about the stage box?

179
00:12:36,800 --> 00:12:38,057
How much?

180
00:12:39,592 --> 00:12:41,127
One pound, please.

181
00:12:41,627 --> 00:12:42,362
That's a small box.

182
00:12:43,500 --> 00:12:46,132
-How many are you?
-We are one.

183
00:12:46,733 --> 00:12:48,167
Any further orders, Mr. De Thrill?

184
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:50,169
Just wait outside.

185
00:12:53,740 --> 00:12:57,100
On no account is Mr De Thrill
to be disturbed, woman. Get it?

186
00:12:57,300 --> 00:12:58,378
Really!

187
00:13:03,900 --> 00:13:07,053
Why does she have such
blinking big plates of meat, Alf?

188
00:13:07,053 --> 00:13:08,788
Stop worrying
and try that for size.

189
00:13:10,523 --> 00:13:12,300
Rosemary and Mr. __,
they know well.

190
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:13,500
-It fits!
-Yes?

191
00:13:13,600 --> 00:13:15,528
Oh, we'll find the other one
and you're ready for the ball.

192
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:21,134
You're going on?

193
00:13:23,069 --> 00:13:23,803
All the best.

194
00:13:27,673 --> 00:13:29,575
You're not wearing those, are you?

195
00:13:44,424 --> 00:13:47,226
But you are beautiful.

196
00:14:01,441 --> 00:14:02,241
Good luck.

197
00:14:07,713 --> 00:14:09,982
All this in one day is too much.

198
00:14:11,050 --> 00:14:12,700
Come on, Cinderella.

199
00:14:14,200 --> 00:14:15,221
You're on.

200
00:14:17,457 --> 00:14:19,859
How perfectly ripping!

201
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:22,295
Our very first carnival ball.

202
00:14:23,629 --> 00:14:25,298
"En français", of course.

203
00:14:25,298 --> 00:14:27,266
I can't wait for this evening!

204
00:14:27,266 --> 00:14:29,569
My frock is a dream.

205
00:14:29,569 --> 00:14:31,971
So is mine.
And rather daring too.

206
00:14:31,971 --> 00:14:34,941
I'm sure Mme. Dubonnet
will be furious.

207
00:14:35,541 --> 00:14:36,476
Not she!

208
00:14:36,476 --> 00:14:40,900
I bet she'll turn up in something
frightfully shocking.

209
00:14:42,700 --> 00:14:44,700
Not De Thrill,
the famous movie director?

210
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:47,400
How do I know what
sort of a thrill he is?

211
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:50,300
Look for yourself.
He is in the stage box.

212
00:14:50,400 --> 00:14:51,800
Why didn't you say so?

213
00:14:59,098 --> 00:15:00,566
Yes, it's him.

214
00:15:01,334 --> 00:15:03,603
Word's got about.
My reputation will be made!

215
00:15:04,900 --> 00:15:07,000
No. Will be ruined.
That girl!

216
00:15:10,943 --> 00:15:13,000
That girl. She can't go on.
We must stop her.

217
00:15:13,100 --> 00:15:15,600
He don't think I'm any good.
I can't go on now.

218
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,300
Bring down the curtain.
We'll send the audience home.

219
00:15:18,400 --> 00:15:20,219
Then I'll go and refund the money.

220
00:15:20,219 --> 00:15:23,400
Wait. Let me think.
__

221
00:15:24,500 --> 00:15:27,900
Here comes Polly Browne
across the tennis courts.

222
00:15:28,100 --> 00:15:30,700
-Polly Browne?
-Yes.

223
00:15:30,900 --> 00:15:32,900
And she's carrying a letter.

224
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:35,268
Hello, Polly.

225
00:15:39,539 --> 00:15:41,541
Oh, Polly! Just think!

226
00:15:42,100 --> 00:15:44,810
London's great theatre land
waiting for you!

227
00:15:45,678 --> 00:15:48,614
His Majesty, the Prince of Wales,
the Duchess, the Royalty,

228
00:15:48,614 --> 00:15:50,960
the Duke of York, the Queen…

229
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:53,300
That's a nice ring.
Hold your tongue, woman.

230
00:15:53,340 --> 00:15:55,500
It's Hollywood calling,
not the Palace.

231
00:15:57,400 --> 00:15:58,324
Listen to me.

232
00:15:59,100 --> 00:16:00,560
The careers and lives

233
00:16:00,600 --> 00:16:04,000
of all these boys and girls
are depending on you.

234
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:07,800
I'm not asking for myself.
But do it for them.

235
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:09,300
Polly, listen to me!

236
00:16:09,800 --> 00:16:11,671
You are going out there
as a youngster.

237
00:16:12,572 --> 00:16:14,500
You've got to
come back a star.

238
00:16:15,100 --> 00:16:16,800
Now get out there
and do your damnedest.

239
00:16:16,900 --> 00:16:18,900
-Hello, Polly!
-Hello, everyone!

240
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:20,200
Where is Rita?

241
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:22,960
She got her foot
caught in the tram line.

242
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:24,300
She's in the hospital.

243
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:34,594
Hello, everyone.

244
00:16:34,594 --> 00:16:36,062
Where have you been?

245
00:16:39,300 --> 00:16:41,000
Hello, everyone.

246
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:42,700
Where have you been?

247
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:47,006
We dashed into town this morning
to collect our costumes for the carnival ball.

248
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,700
We couldn't wait
until Monsieur Gaston delivered them.

249
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,260
You must see mine, Polly.
You'll adore it.

250
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:53,713
Or mine!

251
00:16:53,900 --> 00:16:56,182
-You'll be green with envy.
-Envy!

252
00:16:56,182 --> 00:17:00,400
You know we'll all be jealous
of Polly when she gets hers.

253
00:17:00,700 --> 00:17:03,122
What are you going as, Polly?

254
00:17:05,858 --> 00:17:07,727
I'm going as Pierrette.

255
00:17:08,494 --> 00:17:11,030
Pierrette! How divine!

256
00:17:11,600 --> 00:17:13,432
Now do tell us your secret, Polly.

257
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:16,135
What secret?

258
00:17:17,100 --> 00:17:19,400
If you are going
as Pierrette,

259
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:22,200
who is going

260
00:17:23,400 --> 00:17:24,777
as Pierrot?

261
00:17:27,647 --> 00:17:29,949
I still want it to be a secret.

262
00:17:33,819 --> 00:17:35,400
I've had another letter

263
00:17:35,900 --> 00:17:37,123
from Paris.

264
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:39,659
From Paris! How marvellous!

265
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:42,400
And what does he say?

266
00:17:53,800 --> 00:17:55,400
He says he's

267
00:17:56,800 --> 00:17:58,678
motoring down overnight.

268
00:18:04,100 --> 00:18:05,000
In fact

269
00:18:06,700 --> 00:18:09,600
he should be here
any moment now.

270
00:18:09,689 --> 00:18:11,123
How thrilling!

271
00:18:11,123 --> 00:18:13,159
And how does he sign himself?

272
00:18:13,159 --> 00:18:14,300
Does he say

273
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:16,962
"Passionately yours"?

274
00:18:16,962 --> 00:18:20,166
Or "yours adoringly"?

275
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:24,270
Or does he just say
"With all my love"?

276
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:27,273
Do tell us about him, Polly.

277
00:18:29,300 --> 00:18:30,710
There ain't very much to tell, really.

278
00:18:31,877 --> 00:18:34,013
I expect you know how I feel
as well as I do.

279
00:18:38,400 --> 00:18:41,260
Any girl who's reached the age

280
00:18:41,300 --> 00:18:45,157
of seventeen or thereabouts

281
00:18:45,725 --> 00:18:50,730
has but one desire in view

282
00:18:50,730 --> 00:18:51,764
Eyes and teeth.

283
00:18:52,798 --> 00:18:55,460
She knows she has reached the stage

284
00:18:55,500 --> 00:18:59,660
of needing one to care about

285
00:18:59,700 --> 00:19:04,510
Nothing else would really do

286
00:19:07,400 --> 00:19:10,560
Childhood games are left behind

287
00:19:10,600 --> 00:19:14,460
And her heart takes wing

288
00:19:14,500 --> 00:19:17,860
Hoping that it soon will find

289
00:19:17,900 --> 00:19:22,228
Just one thing

290
00:19:24,363 --> 00:19:26,332
We've got to have

291
00:19:26,332 --> 00:19:28,768
We plot to have

292
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:33,660
For it's so dreary
not to have

293
00:19:33,700 --> 00:19:36,809
that certain thing called

294
00:19:37,100 --> 00:19:39,278
"the boy friend"

295
00:19:42,382 --> 00:19:44,660
We scheme about
and dream about

296
00:19:44,900 --> 00:19:47,860
And we've been known
to scream about

297
00:19:47,900 --> 00:19:50,500
that certain thing called
"the boy friend"

298
00:19:51,900 --> 00:19:54,460
He is really a necessity

299
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:56,400
If you want to get on

300
00:19:56,440 --> 00:20:00,660
And we might as well confess it
He is a "sine qua non"

301
00:20:01,300 --> 00:20:03,800
We sigh for him
and cry for him

302
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:05,900
and we would gladly
die for him

303
00:20:05,940 --> 00:20:09,475
that certain thing called
"the boy friend"

304
00:20:16,215 --> 00:20:20,100
A piano and drums.
What must De Thrill think?

305
00:20:20,900 --> 00:20:24,200
If only we had money
what a spectacle I'd show them.

306
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:27,000
A royal command
performance.

307
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:25,000
We plead to have

308
00:21:25,100 --> 00:21:26,518
We need to have

309
00:21:26,518 --> 00:21:29,360
In fact our poor hearts
bleed to have

310
00:21:29,400 --> 00:21:33,459
That certain thing called
"the boy friend"

311
00:22:50,900 --> 00:22:52,972
We'd save for him

312
00:22:53,800 --> 00:22:55,774
and slave for him

313
00:22:56,900 --> 00:23:02,800
We'd even
misbehave for him

314
00:23:03,900 --> 00:23:08,200
That certain thing called

315
00:23:08,400 --> 00:23:11,957
"the boy friend"

316
00:23:13,100 --> 00:23:15,660
Life without us is impossible

317
00:23:15,700 --> 00:23:17,800
And devoid of all charms

318
00:23:18,100 --> 00:23:20,660
No amount of idle gossip'll

319
00:23:20,700 --> 00:23:24,600
Keep them out of our arms

320
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:28,860
We're blue without

321
00:23:28,900 --> 00:23:32,260
Can't do without

322
00:23:32,300 --> 00:23:37,100
Our dreams just won't come true without

323
00:23:38,100 --> 00:23:41,800
That certain thing called

324
00:23:42,300 --> 00:23:45,824
"the boy friend"

325
00:23:46,300 --> 00:23:49,294
Polly, the spirit of ecstasy?
Ridiculous!

326
00:23:50,900 --> 00:23:53,900
Oh, no!
She's forgotten the steps!

327
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:30,235
Do a "Ruby Keeler".

328
00:24:37,300--> 00:24:38,210
Go on.

329
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:53,660
-She is doing all right.
-All right for Pygmalion.

330
00:24:53,700 --> 00:24:56,395
She is supposed to come
from Westminster, not Wa Ping.

331
00:24:59,100 --> 00:25:02,800
Boys, you know you are not allowed
on the privacies. You must leave at once.

332
00:25:02,900 --> 00:25:06,238
-See you on the plage.
-Do not be late.

333
00:25:07,873 --> 00:25:09,108
Goodbye!

334
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:13,378
But you still haven't told us
much about him, Polly.

335
00:25:13,378 --> 00:25:15,900
Not even his christian name.

336
00:25:16,100 --> 00:25:17,616
What is it, Polly?

337
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:23,500
Girls!
Here comes Mme. Dubonnet!

338
00:25:47,200 --> 00:25:48,580
This is no way to behave.

339
00:25:49,400 --> 00:25:51,717
All of you to your classrooms

340
00:25:54,953 --> 00:25:57,960
where Mlle. Alice
is waiting to instruct you

341
00:25:58,000 --> 00:25:59,258
in "petit point".

342
00:26:06,900 --> 00:26:07,866
Rita, Rita.

343
00:26:08,367 --> 00:26:09,935
Play it like Rita.

344
00:26:16,600 --> 00:26:19,600
I wish to have a little word
with you, "ma petite".

345
00:26:19,800 --> 00:26:22,047
Promenade with me
into "le jardin".

346
00:26:22,800 --> 00:26:24,783
You can help me
gather some hollyhocks.

347
00:26:27,352 --> 00:26:29,060
Do not be frightened,
"ma chère",

348
00:26:29,100 --> 00:26:30,500
you have done
nothing wrong.

349
00:26:30,900 --> 00:26:34,326
I merely wished to ask
if you are coming to the ball tonight.

350
00:26:35,227 --> 00:26:37,696
Yes, of course.
I've ordered my frock.

351
00:26:38,200 --> 00:26:39,865
I'm going as Pierrette.

352
00:26:40,500 --> 00:26:42,868
So you have a friend
to take you?

353
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:47,000
I had a letter today.
He's arriving by car from Paris.

354
00:26:47,200 --> 00:26:48,473
From Paris.

355
00:26:49,500 --> 00:26:51,343
Yes. From Paris.

356
00:26:56,014 --> 00:26:58,483
Onion. You've got to cry.

357
00:27:01,386 --> 00:27:04,823
So why is this letter
postmarked form Nice?

358
00:27:09,995 --> 00:27:12,331
Never mind, my little Polly.

359
00:27:12,900 --> 00:27:15,560
Your secret is safe with me.

360
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:17,400
"Soyez gaie" and trust me

361
00:27:18,400 --> 00:27:21,106
Dry your eyes.

362
00:27:21,106 --> 00:27:22,741
Change your tunic.

363
00:27:23,842 --> 00:27:25,410
You're dancing à la grecque.

364
00:27:27,246 --> 00:27:29,881
No! I won't do it!

365
00:27:30,415 --> 00:27:34,152
A West End artist
act with an amateur? Never!

366
00:27:34,853 --> 00:27:36,955
We've enough cockneys
in this show as it is.

367
00:27:39,124 --> 00:27:41,260
And with De Thrill up front, too!

368
00:27:41,260 --> 00:27:43,500
He'll think he's watching
a variety act.

369
00:27:43,700 --> 00:27:47,700
You'll be expecting me to sing
"Any old iron" next.

370
00:27:49,300 --> 00:27:51,350
Any old iron

371
00:27:51,600 --> 00:27:53,872
You look neat
Talk about a treat

372
00:27:53,872 --> 00:27:55,660
You look so dapper
from your napper to your feet

373
00:27:55,700 --> 00:27:56,880
Dressed in style,
brand-new tile,

374
00:27:56,920 --> 00:27:58,360
with your father's
old green tie on

375
00:27:58,400 --> 00:28:00,600
But I wouldn't give you tuppence
for your old watch and chain,

376
00:28:00,700 --> 00:28:02,500
Old iron, old iron

377
00:28:05,700 --> 00:28:08,200
That's it!
You're a Cockney junk dealer.

378
00:28:08,300 --> 00:28:10,360
Made your fortune
in scrap metal after the war.

379
00:28:10,400 --> 00:28:12,760
You want to better yourself
and Polly too.

380
00:28:12,924 --> 00:28:14,660
You're trying to
live down your past.

381
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:16,728
I'll write it.
We'll save the show yet.

382
00:28:18,830 --> 00:28:20,065
I won't do it.

383
00:28:22,134 --> 00:28:23,335
Anyone got a fountain pen?

384
00:28:23,335 --> 00:28:25,000
I have one, Mr Max.

385
00:28:25,100 --> 00:28:26,300
Emphasis will?

386
00:28:26,400 --> 00:28:28,300
-Paper, paper.
-Here you are.

387
00:28:30,600 --> 00:28:32,660
I want you all to do your best.
Tell the boys I haven't time.

388
00:28:32,700 --> 00:28:35,500
Tell them to dance like Nijinsky.
De Thrill is up front.

389
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:38,800
Not De Thrill,
the __ deal manager from Cable Street?

390
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:41,760
No, it must be De Thrill,
the great Hollywood director

391
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:44,960
talent spotting
for its new, super, colossal,

392
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,760
all-talking,
all-singing, all-dancing

393
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:50,796
famous musical.

394
00:28:51,100 --> 00:28:52,764
Oh, that one!

395
00:29:07,813 --> 00:29:08,480
Hi, toots.

396
00:29:09,481 --> 00:29:10,300
How's Pol doing?

397
00:29:12,117 --> 00:29:15,500
Quite promising, actually.
Care for a puff?

398
00:29:17,500 --> 00:29:18,724
It might stunt my growth.

399
00:29:26,198 --> 00:29:28,967
I say, that's a kicky step.

400
00:29:30,100 --> 00:29:30,900
Who taught you that?

401
00:29:31,500 --> 00:29:32,471
Search me, toots.

402
00:29:33,205 --> 00:29:34,706
As a kid, I was kicked in the head

403
00:29:36,375 --> 00:29:37,442
and when I came to,

404
00:29:39,077 --> 00:29:40,412
amnesia…

405
00:29:43,215 --> 00:29:45,484
How on earth did that happen?

406
00:29:46,184 --> 00:29:47,886
You've heard of the Russian Revolution.

407
00:29:52,991 --> 00:29:53,892
And all that jazz.

408
00:29:53,892 --> 00:29:54,826
Yes.

409
00:29:56,695 --> 00:29:59,698
I'm told I was
on the steps of Odessa

410
00:30:05,400 --> 00:30:07,406
when the Whites went bananas.

411
00:30:11,543 --> 00:30:15,046
When I woke up all I could remember
was how to tapdance.

412
00:30:16,100 --> 00:30:17,516
Fascinating.

413
00:30:18,683 --> 00:30:21,286
Plus the name of one step:
the double-trip,

414
00:30:23,155 --> 00:30:24,222
Maxie-Ford,

415
00:30:26,224 --> 00:30:27,500
with a Knickerbocker break.

416
00:30:35,600 --> 00:30:37,235
What happened to your parents?

417
00:30:38,270 --> 00:30:39,137
I don't know.

418
00:30:40,572 --> 00:30:41,807
I never heard from anybody.

419
00:30:46,144 --> 00:30:47,312
I guess they were done in.

420
00:30:53,351 --> 00:30:56,200
Anyway, since I spoke American

421
00:30:56,300 --> 00:30:59,825
I was shipped off to the States
where they put me in an orphanage.

422
00:31:00,292 --> 00:31:01,326
What was that like?

423
00:31:01,326 --> 00:31:03,929
It was crummy.
They wouldn't even let me tapdance.

424
00:31:06,465 --> 00:31:08,099
One dark night

425
00:31:08,099 --> 00:31:10,669
at the ripe old age of six and a half

426
00:31:11,503 --> 00:31:13,805
I ran away to New York,

427
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,400
to Manhattan, to Times Square,

428
00:31:17,700 --> 00:31:20,300
to Broadway!

429
00:31:22,500 --> 00:31:24,316
Where I became a baby star.

430
00:31:29,287 --> 00:31:31,623
I'm tapping down Broadway

431
00:31:32,491 --> 00:31:34,559
Just tapping down Broadway

432
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:38,663
Because Broadway
Is my tap, slap, happy home

433
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:45,770
Then I outgrew my short pants

434
00:31:46,100 --> 00:31:48,540
and it was curtains for Tiny Tom.

435
00:31:50,300 --> 00:31:53,211
You wouldn't be pulling
a fellow's leg, would you?

436
00:31:54,279 --> 00:31:56,448
Every word's the truth.

437
00:31:56,900 --> 00:31:58,016
Cub Scout's oath.

438
00:31:58,800 --> 00:31:59,800
There's our cue.

439
00:32:02,800 --> 00:32:03,321
Ready?

440
00:32:03,321 --> 00:32:04,890
That was marvellous.

441
00:32:05,900 --> 00:32:08,360
But Tommy, could we
take it easy this afternoon?

442
00:32:08,400 --> 00:32:10,862
I've got the most
appalling headache.

443
00:32:12,564 --> 00:32:13,565
Okay, toots.

444
00:32:13,565 --> 00:32:15,634
I'll give it
the old matinee soft sale.

445
00:32:40,892 --> 00:32:43,562
Please, could you give this
to the maitre d'?

446
00:32:43,900 --> 00:32:45,564
-Oui, Mademoiselle.
-Thank you.

447
00:32:55,907 --> 00:32:57,175
-Guess who!
-Tommy!

448
00:32:57,842 --> 00:32:59,578
Goodness me!
Where I am?

449
00:32:59,578 --> 00:33:01,947
Gosh! You did make a chap jump.

450
00:33:03,048 --> 00:33:04,616
Fancy meeting you here.

451
00:33:04,616 --> 00:33:07,586
I live here. Do you wanna come up
and see my etchings?

452
00:33:07,586 --> 00:33:09,588
I say. Please.

453
00:33:09,588 --> 00:33:11,856
Please! I must leave at once.

454
00:33:11,856 --> 00:33:13,760
I'm just here on an errand

455
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:16,428
for Mme Dubonnet arrangements
for the carnival ball tonight.

456
00:33:17,095 --> 00:33:20,732
If she were to find out
I'd be asked to leave under a cloud.

457
00:33:21,099 --> 00:33:23,902
I'm not letting you go
until you promise me one thing.

458
00:33:23,902 --> 00:33:26,738
-What is that?
-You know as well as I do.

459
00:33:26,738 --> 00:33:28,260
-Do I?
-Of course, you do.

460
00:33:28,300 --> 00:33:30,160
I want you to promise
that tonight

461
00:33:30,200 --> 00:33:32,500
you're gonna dance
every dance at the ball with me.

462
00:33:32,600 --> 00:33:35,400
Oh, that!
That's out of the question.

463
00:33:35,800 --> 00:33:38,249
Come on, Maisie. Be a sports.

464
00:33:38,249 --> 00:33:40,785
You know there's nobody
I wanna dance with but you.

465
00:33:40,785 --> 00:33:42,020
Really?

466
00:33:42,387 --> 00:33:43,788
I don't believe you.

467
00:33:48,200 --> 00:33:51,900
Listen, baby, to my plea

468
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:55,900
Won't you come dancing with me?

469
00:33:56,700 --> 00:34:00,071
be my baby and say "yes"

470
00:34:01,239 --> 00:34:04,676
Or else I'm done for, I guess

471
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:07,979
To dance with you is thrilling

472
00:34:07,979 --> 00:34:11,282
to my poor ego

473
00:34:11,683 --> 00:34:14,560
So baby, say you're willing

474
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:19,190
to shake a leg

475
00:34:19,190 --> 00:34:22,360
Won't you Charleston with me

476
00:34:23,762 --> 00:34:26,665
Won't you Charleston with me

477
00:34:28,366 --> 00:34:31,900
And while the band is playing
that old vo-de-o-do

478
00:34:32,300 --> 00:34:34,239
around we will go

479
00:34:34,800 --> 00:34:36,300
together we'll show them

480
00:34:36,500 --> 00:34:39,711
How the Charleston is done

481
00:34:40,900 --> 00:34:44,883
We'll surprise everyone

482
00:34:45,250 --> 00:34:46,785
Just think what heaven

483
00:34:47,118 --> 00:34:48,760
it's gonna be

484
00:34:48,800 --> 00:34:52,691
if you will Charleston with me

485
00:34:53,491 --> 00:34:56,500
Will you Charleston with me

486
00:34:57,462 --> 00:35:01,533
Will you Charleston with me

487
00:35:01,900 --> 00:35:06,037
And while the band is playing
that old vo-de-o-do

488
00:35:06,037 --> 00:35:07,572
around we will go

489
00:35:08,239 --> 00:35:09,507
together we'll show them

490
00:35:09,900 --> 00:35:13,300
How the Charleston is done

491
00:35:13,400 --> 00:35:17,849
We'll surprise everyone

492
00:35:20,400 --> 00:35:21,853
She's double-crossed.

493
00:35:22,700 --> 00:35:24,956
De Thrill is in the stage box.

494
00:37:02,100 --> 00:37:04,500
He told me when I joined you
he was a Noël Coward poet.

495
00:37:04,600 --> 00:37:07,900
They don't expect Noël
to talk Cockney --do you--
any more than the Queen!

496
00:37:08,200 --> 00:37:09,700
I can act posh.

497
00:37:09,800 --> 00:37:12,300
Act posh? Harken that!

498
00:37:12,400 --> 00:37:14,632
De Thrill wouldn't understand
a word of it.

499
00:37:14,632 --> 00:37:17,836
It's a foreign language
to them Yanks. It's not English.

500
00:37:17,836 --> 00:37:19,860
Do you think I'm a character, man!

501
00:37:19,900 --> 00:37:21,760
You're hardly a Jew,
are you, darling?

502
00:37:21,800 --> 00:37:23,000
Please, keep our memoire a--

503
00:37:23,100 --> 00:37:25,460
The child is not that bad.
She's got a little talent.

504
00:37:25,500 --> 00:37:28,200
Talent? She'll never make the West End
in a million years.

505
00:37:29,300 --> 00:37:30,548
Let's be honest, darling.

506
00:37:30,548 --> 00:37:33,600
The nearest you ever got to the West End
was "Harrow on the Hill"

507
00:37:34,500 --> 00:37:36,160
Unless you count
the twice-nightlies.

508
00:37:36,200 --> 00:37:39,023
Have you forgotten that charity matinee
I gave at Croydon?

509
00:37:39,023 --> 00:37:42,227
I was in that show!
Cockney Capers.

510
00:37:42,227 --> 00:37:44,200
You sang "Henry VIII"

511
00:37:45,400 --> 00:37:47,065
There you are.
Four tickets.

512
00:37:47,065 --> 00:37:48,960
-What about me?
-You talk awfuly refined.

513
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:50,969
You shouldn't find it too difficult.

514
00:37:52,337 --> 00:37:53,872
I won't do it!

515
00:37:55,406 --> 00:37:56,474
Unless I play it straight.

516
00:37:58,509 --> 00:37:58,910
It's perfect.

517
00:37:59,744 --> 00:38:01,579
-Have you fixed it up?
-Here, it won't come off.

518
00:38:01,579 --> 00:38:02,914
Just this one as well.

519
00:38:04,482 --> 00:38:07,800
Polly, before
your parents arrive

520
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:10,860
I want you to tell me
just one thing.

521
00:38:10,900 --> 00:38:11,892
Yes, Madame?

522
00:38:12,800 --> 00:38:17,760
How is it that one
so sweet and charming as you are

523
00:38:17,800 --> 00:38:20,231
acts to pretend to have

524
00:38:20,231 --> 00:38:22,734
--how do you say?--
boyfriend,

525
00:38:22,734 --> 00:38:25,904
and to write yourself love letters?

526
00:38:26,571 --> 00:38:28,239
It's because of my father, Madame.

527
00:38:28,239 --> 00:38:29,274
Your father?

528
00:38:30,900 --> 00:38:35,160
Before Kaiser Wilhelm
and the horrible war
we were terribly poor.

529
00:38:35,200 --> 00:38:39,000
Daddy was a scrap-metal merchant
and I was a little match-girl.

530
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:42,420
But after the armistice
he made his fortune.

531
00:38:42,700 --> 00:38:44,160
He bought up
all the Allies' arms cheap

532
00:38:44,200 --> 00:38:45,924
and now we are terribly
nouveau rich

533
00:38:46,424 --> 00:38:48,760
and when he dies
I shall be extremely wealthy

534
00:38:48,800 --> 00:38:51,460
and he thinks that every man
who makes advances to me

535
00:38:51,500 --> 00:38:53,064
is just after my millions.

536
00:38:54,700 --> 00:38:57,936
There. He forbids you
to have a boyfriend.

537
00:38:59,270 --> 00:39:01,700
Well. Practically.

538
00:39:02,307 --> 00:39:03,741
So you invent him?

539
00:39:04,242 --> 00:39:05,310
Yes, I'm afraid so.

540
00:39:07,111 --> 00:39:08,212
I see.

541
00:39:08,212 --> 00:39:09,847
Poor little rich girl.

542
00:39:10,782 --> 00:39:13,460
I too had a letter today
from your father.

543
00:39:13,500 --> 00:39:16,154
He is coming here
this morning.

544
00:39:19,991 --> 00:39:21,559
Daddy? Coming here?

545
00:39:24,295 --> 00:39:28,166
He is coming from Toulon
on business

546
00:39:28,166 --> 00:39:30,802
and when I see him

547
00:39:31,469 --> 00:39:33,738
I will have a little word with him.

548
00:39:35,039 --> 00:39:36,641
He won't listen.

549
00:39:37,508 --> 00:39:38,900
We shall see.

550
00:39:39,500 --> 00:39:41,779
"Attends", my little Isadoras.

551
00:39:41,779 --> 00:39:44,983
Today we dance "Narcissus"

552
00:47:54,805 --> 00:47:56,173
Bless you, "mes enfants".

553
00:47:56,173 --> 00:48:00,177
May the gods pour libations
of happiness in your houses.

554
00:48:01,011 --> 00:48:03,380
Run along, my Isadoras

555
00:48:03,380 --> 00:48:06,383
Madame wishes to meditate.

556
00:48:11,021 --> 00:48:13,190
Really! Thank you.

557
00:48:35,600 --> 00:48:36,900
Here.

558
00:48:44,388 --> 00:48:47,024
How do you do, Madame?

559
00:48:47,700 --> 00:48:49,100
How do you do?

560
00:49:03,674 --> 00:49:04,542
Monsieur Browne

561
00:49:05,342 --> 00:49:08,612
Or should I say,
"mon petit Percy"?

562
00:49:09,580 --> 00:49:11,282
I don't follow you, Madame.

563
00:49:11,900 --> 00:49:13,000
Mais oui, mon chère,

564
00:49:16,620 --> 00:49:19,423
Do you not remember
your little Kiki?

565
00:49:21,859 --> 00:49:24,028
Good heavens!
This is impossible!

566
00:49:25,396 --> 00:49:26,597
Most awkward.

567
00:49:26,897 --> 00:49:27,898
How could it be?

568
00:49:28,465 --> 00:49:31,902
After all we have been
to each other.

569
00:49:35,406 --> 00:49:38,742
Have  you forgotten
Armistice night?

570
00:49:39,577 --> 00:49:42,079
Or when you kissed me on

571
00:49:45,316 --> 00:49:47,284
the Champs Elysees.

572
00:50:17,500 --> 00:50:22,319
Yes, Madam.
I have completely forgotten.

573
00:50:23,187 --> 00:50:24,455
Surely not, cheri.

574
00:50:25,756 --> 00:50:29,326
I wore a white dress
and you wore in uniform.

575
00:50:30,394 --> 00:50:34,932
Later on, I called you
"my pretty private".

576
00:50:34,932 --> 00:50:36,500
Then we drank champagne.

577
00:50:36,600 --> 00:50:38,200
Everyone was happy.

578
00:50:38,400 --> 00:50:41,538
Then, two little love birds

579
00:50:41,538 --> 00:50:43,140
flew over our heads.

580
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:28,185
So, the kid stepped
into the star shoes.

581
00:51:29,600 --> 00:51:31,822
Gosh, Rita, I'm sorry.

582
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:33,600
Does it hurt?

583
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:36,200
Of course it hurts.

584
00:51:36,600 --> 00:51:38,462
When someone else
takes your place.

585
00:51:38,462 --> 00:51:40,698
But I could never act
to be another Rita Monroe.

586
00:51:40,698 --> 00:51:43,000
No one could, dear. Ever.

587
00:51:44,268 --> 00:51:46,203
But you might just get by.

588
00:51:47,604 --> 00:51:48,405
One day.

589
00:51:50,174 --> 00:51:51,442
Now you're just

590
00:51:52,609 --> 00:51:54,860
a nervous, skinny kid

591
00:51:54,900 --> 00:51:58,348
overwhelmed of the impossibility
of trying to save the show.

592
00:51:58,348 --> 00:52:00,060
And on top of that
you have to face

593
00:52:00,100 --> 00:52:03,460
the bitter disappointment
of all my fans out there

594
00:52:04,600 --> 00:52:07,925
who screamed and saved their pennies
week after week

595
00:52:08,200 --> 00:52:11,760
to come here this afternoon
to see that special kind of magic

596
00:52:11,800 --> 00:52:15,399
that only their Rita
can give them.

597
00:52:19,236 --> 00:52:22,139
Do you know your steps?
Show me the Buck & Wing on your first duet.

598
00:52:28,946 --> 00:52:29,913
Sorry, Rita.

599
00:52:32,500 --> 00:52:35,400
Fake it. That's what I always did
whenever I was ill.

600
00:52:35,500 --> 00:52:37,955
Chances are they'll never notice.

601
00:52:38,255 --> 00:52:41,191
There is that tricky obbligato
in the Pierrette number.

602
00:52:59,500 --> 00:53:02,813
That Parkhill woman is sure
to be singing flat.

603
00:53:03,313 --> 00:53:04,414
They'll never notice.

604
00:53:04,414 --> 00:53:07,684
If you do forget your lines,
"ad lib".

605
00:53:07,684 --> 00:53:10,654
It'll destroy the rest of the cast
but at least you won't dry.

606
00:53:13,657 --> 00:53:16,126
Pull yourself together
and don't worry.

607
00:53:16,600 --> 00:53:18,195
We'll find a replacement tomorrow.

608
00:53:20,097 --> 00:53:21,100
Now get out there

609
00:53:22,100 --> 00:53:24,200
and be so great

610
00:53:25,600 --> 00:53:27,271
you'll make me hate you.

611
00:53:27,271 --> 00:53:29,406
Thank you, Rita
you're really too kind.

612
00:53:32,176 --> 00:53:33,677
Sweet.

613
00:53:34,611 --> 00:53:39,700
I could be happy with you

614
00:53:41,685 --> 00:53:47,658
if you could be happy with me

615
00:53:58,836 --> 00:54:01,360
Then, from a little cafe

616
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:04,575
came the strands of a waltz.

617
00:54:07,511 --> 00:54:08,545
How did it go?

618
00:54:25,162 --> 00:54:28,532
I still recall so tenderly

619
00:54:28,532 --> 00:54:31,068
the night when first we met

620
00:54:32,169 --> 00:54:34,660
The memory's so dear to me

621
00:54:34,700 --> 00:54:38,942
So how can you forget?

622
00:54:43,881 --> 00:54:47,217
Fancy forgetting

623
00:54:47,217 --> 00:54:50,087
the love that we knew

624
00:54:50,087 --> 00:54:54,057
When we were fancy free

625
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:58,528
Fancy forgetting

626
00:54:59,129 --> 00:55:01,265
What I said to you

627
00:55:02,466 --> 00:55:04,902
And what you said to me

628
00:55:08,739 --> 00:55:11,475
Though the years go by

629
00:55:11,475 --> 00:55:14,444
and our youth is gone

630
00:55:14,978 --> 00:55:17,581
Memories don't die

631
00:55:18,315 --> 00:55:22,319
like a song, they linger on

632
00:55:24,321 --> 00:55:26,223
So just when I thought

633
00:55:26,223 --> 00:55:30,627
you'd remember it too

634
00:55:34,800 --> 00:55:37,900
Fancy, just fancy you

635
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:41,772
forgetting

636
00:55:49,146 --> 00:55:51,848
I told you I'd play it straight.

637
00:55:53,083 --> 00:55:54,151
Hear him!

638
00:55:56,486 --> 00:55:58,755
I'm really scared now.
I can't remember a thing.

639
00:55:58,755 --> 00:56:00,457
Don't worry.

640
00:56:02,025 --> 00:56:06,096
And Pol, don't try
to copy the others.

641
00:56:06,900 --> 00:56:08,732
If you really mean
what you say on the stage

642
00:56:08,900 --> 00:56:10,701
you can't get it wrong.

643
00:56:11,902 --> 00:56:13,270
Now depart, dear.

644
00:56:50,007 --> 00:56:51,541
Class dismissed.

645
00:56:56,213 --> 00:56:57,047
Girls, I know.

646
00:56:57,047 --> 00:57:00,884
Let's go and try on our costumes
before lunch.

647
00:57:00,884 --> 00:57:02,486
Yes!

648
00:57:03,286 --> 00:57:04,821
Are you coming too, Polly?

649
00:57:04,821 --> 00:57:08,700
I think I'll just stay here.
I'm expecting Daddy any moment.

650
00:57:09,200 --> 00:57:11,495
And aren't you expecting him?

651
00:57:12,362 --> 00:57:13,063
Him?

652
00:57:13,930 --> 00:57:14,865
Yes, of course.

653
00:57:16,700 --> 00:57:20,370
Let's leave her, girls.
She wants to be alone.

654
00:57:21,872 --> 00:57:22,806
Goodbye.

655
00:57:30,600 --> 00:57:32,000
Excusez-moi!

656
00:57:32,916 --> 00:57:33,884
You startled me.

657
00:57:34,300 --> 00:57:37,788
I'm sorry, Miss.
I'm afraid I came in the wrong way.

658
00:57:40,424 --> 00:57:41,758
It's the Villa Caprice, isn't it?

659
00:57:41,758 --> 00:57:42,759
Yes.

660
00:57:43,300 --> 00:57:45,300
I have a package here
for Miss Polly Browne.

661
00:57:45,900 --> 00:57:47,397
Really? How funny.

662
00:57:47,600 --> 00:57:49,699
Funny? Why?

663
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:52,469
Because I'm Polly Browne.

664
00:57:53,600 --> 00:57:55,472
It's a very pretty name.

665
00:57:56,106 --> 00:57:57,641
Thank you.

666
00:57:58,500 --> 00:57:59,900
And you live up to it.

667
00:58:06,100 --> 00:58:08,360
I'm sorry, Miss.
I'm afraid I'm forgetting myself.

668
00:58:08,400 --> 00:58:09,400
Here is your package.

669
00:58:09,800 --> 00:58:10,821
Oh, thank you.

670
00:58:13,924 --> 00:58:15,400
Don't they make a lovely couple?

671
00:58:20,400 --> 00:58:21,400
Sorry.

672
00:58:25,500 --> 00:58:27,200
I packed it myself.

673
00:58:27,500 --> 00:58:30,000
If you don't mind my saying so,
it is a very pretty dress.

674
00:58:30,500 --> 00:58:31,700
Yes, it is, isn't it?

675
00:58:37,314 --> 00:58:38,482
I'm sure that you'll...

676
00:58:38,482 --> 00:58:42,000
I mean, it will be
the prettiest of the ball.

677
00:58:42,552 --> 00:58:44,821
Oh. I don't expect so, really.

678
00:58:45,822 --> 00:58:47,958
I do. In fact, I know it.

679
00:58:54,900 --> 00:58:56,500
Perhaps I'd better be going.

680
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:06,500
Yes. Perhaps you had.

681
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:09,500
Accent! Accent!

682
00:59:10,614 --> 00:59:11,500
I say,

683
00:59:14,885 --> 00:59:16,253
You are English, aren't you?

684
00:59:17,387 --> 00:59:19,000
Yes. As a matter of fact I am.

685
00:59:20,223 --> 00:59:22,500
You don't seem like
a messenger boy somehow.

686
00:59:24,928 --> 00:59:27,597
To tell you the truth,
I don't usually do this sort of thing

687
00:59:28,398 --> 00:59:31,034
but just at the moment
I'm afraid I'm rather on my beam ends.

688
00:59:32,536 --> 00:59:34,004
What a shame.

689
00:59:43,847 --> 00:59:45,649
And at carnival time too?

690
00:59:45,649 --> 00:59:47,350
Yes. It's a pity, isn't it?

691
00:59:48,084 --> 00:59:49,800
I was hoping I'd be able
to go to the ball tonight.

692
00:59:50,900 --> 00:59:51,855
I'll be watching.

693
00:59:51,855 --> 00:59:52,822
Will you?

694
00:59:53,400 --> 00:59:54,500
Yes, of course.

695
00:59:57,327 --> 00:59:58,300
Why don't you came too?

696
00:59:58,900 --> 01:00:01,100
Me? Come to the ball?

697
01:00:01,700 --> 01:00:04,201
Yes, why not?
I've got an extra ticket…

698
01:00:05,200 --> 01:00:09,539
Oh, dear. You must think me
terribly forward.

699
01:00:09,600 --> 01:00:10,760
No, I don't!

700
01:00:13,700 --> 01:00:16,600
I think you're
terribly, terribly…

701
01:00:25,400 --> 01:00:27,791
I don't claim that I am psychic

702
01:00:28,425 --> 01:00:30,527
But one look at you and I kick

703
01:00:31,394 --> 01:00:32,896
Away every scruple

704
01:00:32,896 --> 01:00:36,933
I learnt as a pupil
In school my dear

705
01:00:38,068 --> 01:00:41,238
I'm not one
to make predictions

706
01:00:41,238 --> 01:00:44,140
But I've thrown off all restrictions

707
01:00:44,400 --> 01:00:47,000
And don't mind confessing
I think it's a blessing

708
01:00:47,100 --> 01:00:49,500
That you are here

709
01:00:51,300 --> 01:00:55,900
Now  I'm prepared
To find I'm wrong

710
01:00:56,900 --> 01:01:05,262
I've got a funny feeling
we belong together

711
01:01:06,162 --> 01:01:11,500
I could be happy with you

712
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:17,073
If you could be happy with me

713
01:01:19,009 --> 01:01:24,780
I'd be contented
to live anywhere

714
01:01:24,900 --> 01:01:28,400
What would I care

715
01:01:28,700 --> 01:01:31,520
as long as you are there

716
01:01:32,500 --> 01:01:38,360
Skies may not always be blue

717
01:01:38,700 --> 01:01:43,333
But one thing is clear as can be

718
01:01:44,300 --> 01:01:50,960
I know that I could be happy
with you, my darling

719
01:01:51,000 --> 01:01:54,900
if you could be happy with…

720
01:06:58,900 --> 01:07:00,316
Then you will come
to the ball?

721
01:07:00,783 --> 01:07:02,151
Well, I'll try.

722
01:07:02,500 --> 01:07:03,920
I'll have to see about a costume.

723
01:07:04,900 --> 01:07:07,000
There is a Pierrot's costume
at Gaston's.

724
01:07:07,300 --> 01:07:09,258
Couldn't you borrow it?

725
01:07:09,626 --> 01:07:10,193
I'll see.

726
01:07:11,961 --> 01:07:13,129
How can I let you know?

727
01:07:14,230 --> 01:07:15,400
Let me think.

728
01:07:15,900 --> 01:07:18,635
I'll be on the plage
at 3 o'clock this afternoon,

729
01:07:19,669 --> 01:07:21,037
on the Crazy Golf coast.

730
01:07:22,205 --> 01:07:23,172
Goodbye until then.

731
01:07:27,644 --> 01:07:29,879
And I don't even know his name.

732
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:34,160
Polly, I have a visitor for you.

733
01:07:34,200 --> 01:07:35,760
Daddy, I'm so happy!

734
01:07:35,800 --> 01:07:37,700
Are you, my dear?
I'm glad to hear it.

735
01:07:37,800 --> 01:07:38,960
Has he arrived yet, Polly?

736
01:07:39,000 --> 01:07:40,323
Yes, he's arrived.

737
01:07:42,800 --> 01:07:44,300
He's really arrived.

738
01:07:46,900 --> 01:07:49,300
We're blue without

739
01:07:49,500 --> 01:07:52,000
Can't do without

740
01:07:52,200 --> 01:07:56,700
Our dreams just won't
come true without

741
01:07:57,300 --> 01:08:00,877
That certain thing called

742
01:08:00,877 --> 01:08:04,700
"the boy friend"

743
01:11:19,108 --> 01:11:22,278
In my imagination

744
01:11:22,879 --> 01:11:26,048
I search the star-lit sky so bright

745
01:11:26,048 --> 01:11:28,951
In my imagination

746
01:11:29,685 --> 01:11:33,122
there I saw you in the night

747
01:11:34,223 --> 01:11:36,893
And then one day I found you

748
01:11:37,760 --> 01:11:40,930
How could I help but realise

749
01:11:41,597 --> 01:11:44,033
My lucky star was smiling

750
01:11:44,934 --> 01:11:49,438
right there before my very eyes

751
01:11:50,706 --> 01:11:55,611
You are my lucky star

752
01:11:56,579 --> 01:11:57,679
I saw you from afar

753
01:12:03,819 --> 01:12:07,290
Two lovely eyes,
 at me they were gleamin',

754
01:12:09,091 --> 01:12:10,626
beamin'

755
01:12:12,328 --> 01:12:14,997
I was star-struck

756
01:12:14,997 --> 01:12:20,436
You're all my lucky charms

757
01:12:21,404 --> 01:12:26,609
I'm lucky in your arms

758
01:12:27,500 --> 01:12:30,460
You've opened heaven's portal

759
01:12:30,500 --> 01:12:34,200
Here on earth for this poor mortal

760
01:12:34,300 --> 01:12:40,400
You are my lucky star

761
01:12:41,300 --> 01:12:43,200
Je suis vraiment enchanté, Mademoiselle.

762
01:12:43,700 --> 01:12:46,200
Vous étes charmante.

763
01:12:46,529 --> 01:12:48,297
He says you are lovely, darling.

764
01:12:48,800 --> 01:12:49,966
You speak French?

765
01:12:50,100 --> 01:12:52,100
Mais évidemment, Monsieur

766
01:12:52,300 --> 01:12:55,500
J'ai été éduquée au college
de Brighton.

767
01:12:55,540 --> 01:12:57,800
En français, naturellement.

768
01:12:58,500 --> 01:12:59,300
Charmant.

769
01:12:59,340 --> 01:13:03,600
Monsieur Max et les autres
vous attendent dans votre loge.

770
01:13:06,500 --> 01:13:08,400
Au revoir, Mademoiselle.

771
01:13:10,300 --> 01:13:12,655
That means
"Good bye, Miss".

772
01:13:13,700 --> 01:13:16,559
She's only an understudy,
not a real actress.

773
01:13:29,700 --> 01:13:31,420
I have a few photographs here
about past successes

774
01:13:31,460 --> 01:13:33,142
that might interest you, Mr. De Thrill.

775
01:13:33,200 --> 01:13:35,378
That's me in the Chinese Bungalow.

776
01:13:35,378 --> 01:13:37,146
What have you here?

777
01:13:37,646 --> 01:13:39,815
That's me as Hamlet,
a tragedy.

778
01:13:39,815 --> 01:13:42,351
Me in "Luck Of The Navy".

779
01:14:41,700 --> 01:14:43,279
That champagne costs money.

780
01:14:43,846 --> 01:14:45,081
We should be safe in here.

781
01:14:49,385 --> 01:14:50,986
We thought you were with the others.

782
01:14:54,123 --> 01:14:56,158
Sorry. Excuse us.

783
01:14:57,126 --> 01:14:57,893
Come on, Dulcie.

784
01:15:49,378 --> 01:15:52,300
What a lovely day
What a lovely day

785
01:15:52,400 --> 01:15:55,400
For a dip in the sea

786
01:15:55,500 --> 01:15:58,900
Oh, what fun it will be

787
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:01,891
Won't you come
and have a swim with me?

788
01:16:02,400 --> 01:16:05,960
