-can be charming

1306
01:59:24,357 --> 01:59:26,626
There's dog's dirt
all over your spat, Sir.

1307
01:59:54,187 --> 01:59:57,090
Forgive the outrage, Mr. De Thrill.
The girl has lost her senses.

1308
01:59:57,800 --> 01:59:59,360
She is dismissed.

1309
01:59:59,400 --> 02:00:01,661
She can pack her bags
and leave at the end of the week.

1310
02:00:01,600 --> 02:00:02,700
She's fired.

1311
02:00:03,062 --> 02:00:04,664
You've had your chance
and you've lost it.

1312
02:00:17,600 --> 02:00:19,600
So she came to the ball
after all.

1313
02:00:20,200 --> 02:00:23,016
Poor child.
How sad she looks.

1314
02:00:24,100 --> 02:00:26,186
Let me talk to her, mon vieux.

1315
02:00:27,300 --> 02:00:28,888
I know how she is feeling.

1316
02:00:29,400 --> 02:00:31,858
We all missed you like mad.

1317
02:00:32,600 --> 02:00:33,560
Didn't we, chaps?

1318
02:00:33,600 --> 02:00:35,295
Yes, we did, Polly.

1319
02:00:36,696 --> 02:00:38,331
Polly. You'll never guess
what's happened to us.

1320
02:00:39,699 --> 02:00:42,135
We've all been proposed to.

1321
02:00:42,502 --> 02:00:44,304
But we haven't been accepted yet.

1322
02:00:44,304 --> 02:00:48,107
We are letting them know at midnight.

1323
02:00:48,900 --> 02:00:52,400
Polly, what a shame.
Your fellow turned out to be a…

1324
02:00:52,500 --> 02:00:54,781
A rotter and a cad.

1325
02:00:57,800 --> 02:01:00,119
You do not wish to dance, Polly?

1326
02:01:00,500 --> 02:01:04,490
Until I dance with him, Madame,
I will never dance again.

1327
02:01:05,091 --> 02:01:06,059
Never mind.

1328
02:01:07,393 --> 02:01:09,329
The night is still young.

1329
02:01:13,933 --> 02:01:14,901
You know, Polly,

1330
02:01:16,169 --> 02:01:18,705
when I look at you
in that sweet costume

1331
02:01:20,106 --> 02:01:21,608
you remind me

1332
02:01:22,742 --> 02:01:24,744
of a song I once knew.

1333
02:01:25,178 --> 02:01:25,879
Do I, madam?

1334
02:01:27,046 --> 02:01:28,114
Can you sing it?

1335
02:01:28,915 --> 02:01:29,883
Yes, I think so.

1336
02:01:34,000 --> 02:01:35,989
There is an old French legend

1337
02:01:36,789 --> 02:01:38,691
that's set to an old French tune.

1338
02:01:39,726 --> 02:01:41,628
It tells how Pierrot
loved Pierrette

1339
02:01:42,528 --> 02:01:44,230
under the summer moon

1340
02:01:45,465 --> 02:01:47,734
Every night the lovers meet

1341
02:01:47,734 --> 02:01:49,936
just as the clock strikes nine

1342
02:01:51,471 --> 02:01:54,107
Then he gives her kisses sweet

1343
02:01:54,107 --> 02:01:58,912
As vintage wine

1344
02:02:01,000 --> 02:02:03,283
But alas, one fateful night

1345
02:02:04,617 --> 02:02:06,719
Pierrette is forsworn

1346
02:02:08,087 --> 02:02:10,290
There she stand, forlorn

1347
02:02:10,957 --> 02:02:13,493
till the cold grey dawn

1348
02:02:15,328 --> 02:02:17,430
Poor little Pierrette

1349
02:02:18,598 --> 02:02:19,933
Where's your Pierrot?

1350
02:02:21,434 --> 02:02:24,270
Why are you all alone?

1351
02:02:27,700 --> 02:02:30,276
You should be so fancy-free

1352
02:02:30,500 --> 02:02:33,646
Your heart should be high

1353
02:02:34,400 --> 02:02:36,849
But instead
You hang your head

1354
02:02:37,400 --> 02:02:39,886
And try not to cry

1355
02:02:42,088 --> 02:02:44,457
Poor little Pierrette

1356
02:02:45,300 --> 02:02:47,026
You must not show

1357
02:02:48,400 --> 02:02:52,565
Your dream of love has flown

1358
02:02:55,300 --> 02:02:57,370
Just keep on dancing

1359
02:02:58,200 --> 02:03:00,707
Till the dawn, and then

1360
02:03:02,275 --> 02:03:06,045
He may come back again

1361
02:03:09,300 --> 02:03:11,400
Poor little Pierrette

1362
02:03:11,440 --> 02:03:14,000
Where's your Pierrot?

1363
02:03:14,800 --> 02:03:19,800
Why are you all alone?

1364
02:03:20,600 --> 02:03:22,900
You should be so fancy-free

1365
02:03:22,940 --> 02:03:26,200
Your heart should be high

1366
02:03:26,240 --> 02:03:29,400
But instead
You hang your head

1367
02:03:29,440 --> 02:03:33,400
And try not to cry

1368
02:03:33,440 --> 02:03:36,700
Poor little Pierrette

1369
02:03:36,740 --> 02:03:39,800
You must not show

1370
02:03:39,840 --> 02:03:45,700
Your dream of love has flown

1371
02:03:46,400 --> 02:03:49,000
Just keep on dancing

1372
02:03:49,040 --> 02:03:53,200
Till the dawn, and then

1373
02:03:53,240 --> 02:04:03,500
He may come back again

1374
02:04:07,300 --> 02:04:08,574
May I have this dance?

1375
02:04:09,400 --> 02:04:11,778
I'm afraid I can't dance
with a stranger.

1376
02:04:12,600 --> 02:04:13,813
But I am Pierrot.

1377
02:04:14,600 --> 02:04:16,082
You are Pierrette.

1378
02:04:16,500 --> 02:04:18,451
Surely we are not strangers.

1379
02:04:18,500 --> 02:04:20,153
But I don't know who you are.

1380
02:04:20,700 --> 02:04:23,156
Maybe this will remind you.

1381
02:04:26,392 --> 02:04:28,294
It isn't. It can't be.

1382
02:04:28,700 --> 02:04:29,829
Yes, it's me!

1383
02:04:30,100 --> 02:04:31,000
Tony!

1384
02:04:33,500 --> 02:04:34,534
Polly!

1385
02:04:40,840 --> 02:04:43,042
Dulcie and I made it between us
during the show.

1386
02:04:44,600 --> 02:04:46,700
"Happy first night"

1387
02:04:47,300 --> 02:04:49,549
"I love you. Tony"

1388
02:04:53,100 --> 02:04:54,087
Blow it out.

1389
02:04:57,657 --> 02:04:58,691
Thank you.

1390
02:05:03,196 --> 02:05:04,297
Hubert, it's Tony!

1391
02:05:05,331 --> 02:05:06,699
We find him at last!

1392
02:05:08,334 --> 02:05:09,202
My son!

1393
02:05:09,202 --> 02:05:10,002
Mother!

1394
02:05:13,300 --> 02:05:14,207
Father!

1395
02:05:14,200 --> 02:05:18,344
And whom, may I ask,
is this young man?

1396
02:05:19,000 --> 02:05:23,900
This, Sir, is my son,
the honourable Tony Brockhurst.

1397
02:05:24,500 --> 02:05:26,519
The honourable Tony Brockhurst?

1398
02:05:30,200 --> 02:05:32,425
I'm afraid I'm not
a messenger boy after all.

1399
02:05:33,800 --> 02:05:34,994
Can you forgive me?

1400
02:05:35,900 --> 02:05:37,063
Yes, of course.

1401
02:05:37,600 --> 02:05:41,000
And who, may I ask,
is this young woman?

1402
02:05:41,500 --> 02:05:44,871
That, Madame, is my daughter.

1403
02:05:46,400 --> 02:05:48,341
And I am Percival Browne.

1404
02:05:50,300 --> 02:05:51,844
Not Percival Browne
the millionaire.

1405
02:05:52,979 --> 02:05:54,747
I'm afraid I deceived you too.

1406
02:05:55,615 --> 02:05:57,083
I'm not secretary after all.

1407
02:05:58,518 --> 02:05:59,685
Can you forgive me?

1408
02:06:00,853 --> 02:06:02,855
Of course, my darling.

1409
02:06:04,924 --> 02:06:07,727
It seems that love
is in the air tonight.

1410
02:06:08,300 --> 02:06:09,228
It is indeed.

1411
02:06:10,096 --> 02:06:12,732
I too, Polly, have some news.

1412
02:06:12,732 --> 02:06:14,901
Have you, Daddy? How thrilling.

1413
02:06:15,601 --> 02:06:17,270
May I tell her, Kiki?

1414
02:06:17,937 --> 02:06:21,374
Of course.
She should be the first to know.

1415
02:06:22,742 --> 02:06:23,342
Very well, then. Polly,

1416
02:06:24,243 --> 02:06:26,612
Mme Dubonnet has consented

1417
02:06:27,446 --> 02:06:29,782
to become my wife.

1418
02:06:31,500 --> 02:06:35,087
Maisie, it's midnight.
Have you thought it over?

1419
02:06:35,200 --> 02:06:36,756
-And you?
-And you?

1420
02:06:37,800 --> 02:06:40,092
After due consideration

1421
02:06:40,300 --> 02:06:43,160
we have come to the conclusion

1422
02:06:43,200 --> 02:06:46,599
that the answer is unanimously

1423
02:06:48,000 --> 02:06:49,100
Yes!

1424
02:06:49,300 --> 02:06:50,500
Swell!

1425
02:06:51,000 --> 02:06:52,800
Where should we go for the honeymoon?

1426
02:06:53,000 --> 02:06:54,400
The Riviera.

1427
02:06:55,400 --> 02:06:56,709
Whenever you want,
Mr. De Thrill.

1428
02:06:57,500 --> 02:06:58,900
Background action!

1429
02:06:59,300 --> 02:07:00,300
Stand behind!

1430
02:07:00,600 --> 02:07:03,860
Wriggle your hips and kick up your heels
you'll be surprised how lovely it feels

1431
02:07:03,900 --> 02:07:06,586
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1432
02:07:07,920 --> 02:07:11,090
Wiggle your fingers, wiggle your toes
Just how it started nobody knows

1433
02:07:11,500 --> 02:07:13,726
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1434
02:07:15,100 --> 02:07:18,100
Multi Millionaires
and their little pets do it

1435
02:07:18,400 --> 02:07:20,766
Even maiden ladies
who wear lorgnettes

1436
02:07:20,900 --> 02:07:22,460
have taken to it

1437
02:07:22,500 --> 02:07:26,160
Tell everyone to give out the news
this is the way to shake off the blues

1438
02:07:26,200 --> 02:07:28,800
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1439
02:07:30,643 --> 02:07:31,978
Wait on the set, everybody!

1440
02:07:35,915 --> 02:07:38,150
Get on the dance floor

1441
02:07:38,150 --> 02:07:41,420
get in the swing

1442
02:07:41,420 --> 02:07:43,489
this is the time for

1443
02:07:43,489 --> 02:07:45,992
having a fling

1444
02:07:46,400 --> 02:07:52,500
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1445
02:07:54,634 --> 02:07:57,700
Clap-a your hands
and slap on your thighs

1446
02:07:57,800 --> 02:08:00,400
Grin like a goon
and roll up your eyes

1447
02:08:00,800 --> 02:08:04,577
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1448
02:08:06,200 --> 02:08:10,200
All the bright young things
and their bright young beaux do it

1449
02:08:10,500 --> 02:08:14,900
Even duchesses and their gigolos
have taken to it

1450
02:08:15,300 --> 02:08:17,300
Ain't it terrific? Ain't it the top?

1451
02:08:17,800 --> 02:08:19,892
You gotta dance right on till you drop

1452
02:08:20,000 --> 02:08:22,728
Everybody's doing the Riviera

1453
02:09:18,800 --> 02:09:23,560
I know that I could be happy

1454
02:09:23,600 --> 02:09:27,093
with you, my darling

1455
02:09:43,400 --> 02:09:46,545
If you could be happy

1456
02:09:46,545 --> 02:09:51,000
with me

1457
02:10:53,045 --> 02:10:55,047
Well done. You saved the show.

1458
02:10:55,047 --> 02:10:56,482
A star is born.

1459
02:10:56,900 --> 02:10:59,000
You're welcome to be the star
of a crummy show like this.

1460
02:10:59,800 --> 02:11:01,620
You can understudy
my part tonight, deary.

1461
02:11:02,100 --> 02:11:04,560
The public liked you,
De Thrill liked you. I liked you.

1462
02:11:04,600 --> 02:11:05,960
You can stay on
for another week.

1463
02:11:06,000 --> 02:11:08,100
-At double salary, of course.
-We'll discuss that later.

1464
02:11:08,200 --> 02:11:11,931
We'll discuss the young lady now
if you don't mind.

1465
02:11:12,300 --> 02:11:15,100
She is a Jonah.
I've never known of a force like it!

1466
02:11:15,200 --> 02:11:18,500
Ad-libing at stage,
a family row on stage!

1467
02:11:19,600 --> 02:11:21,807
Cakes and __.

1468
02:11:22,300 --> 02:11:25,400
My professional career
in tatters!

1469
02:11:25,900 --> 02:11:28,800
A hard-earned reputation
ruined!

1470
02:11:28,900 --> 02:11:30,900
And it all started with her!

1471
02:11:31,300 --> 02:11:33,419
Either she goes
or I go.

1472
02:11:33,600 --> 02:11:34,860
That's easily settled.

1473
02:11:34,900 --> 02:11:37,656
I've been thinking for some time
of taking over your part.

1474
02:11:37,656 --> 02:11:41,200
I'm really miscast as
Lord Brockhurst. Far too young.

1475
02:11:41,600 --> 02:11:44,263
Pay no attention to him, Mr. Max.
He is rather overwrought this afternoon.

1476
02:11:44,263 --> 02:11:47,166
Don't bother me now.
De Thrill and I have things…

1477
02:11:50,500 --> 02:11:54,000
Bonjour, Monsieur.
Voulez vous filmer avec moi?

1478
02:11:55,400 --> 02:11:58,400
Das ist für Fräulein Polly.

1479
02:11:59,400 --> 02:12:01,800
For Polly.
Can't you speak German?

1480
02:12:02,700 --> 02:12:03,883
German?

1481
02:12:08,087 --> 02:12:09,688
I think I will make

1482
02:12:12,291 --> 02:12:13,726
"Singin' in the rain"

1483
02:13:20,300 --> 02:13:22,500
I'll send you a postcard
from Hollywood, chaps.

1484
02:13:27,900 --> 02:13:31,400
That'll make you a
lovely smelling lady in Christendom.

1485
02:13:38,500 --> 02:13:39,645
Just rehearsing.

1486
02:14:11,300 --> 02:14:13,000
Wait. Wait. Look!

1487
02:14:24,000 --> 02:14:26,900
You know the double-trip Maxie Ford
with a Knickerbocker break!

1488
02:14:27,200 --> 02:14:29,000
Well, I taught it to you.

1489
02:14:29,200 --> 02:14:30,800
-I thought you were dead!
-I thought you were dead!

1490
02:14:30,900 --> 02:14:32,865
-No, I lost my memory.
-No, I was interned.

1491
02:14:32,865 --> 02:14:35,200
-Pop?
-My son!

1492
02:14:38,270 --> 02:14:39,238
I can't believe it.

1493
02:14:40,906 --> 02:14:41,740
Mr. De Thrill…

1494
02:14:42,608 --> 02:14:44,510
It's all a game.
Goodbye, Miss.

1495
02:14:45,411 --> 02:14:47,079
I hope your headache gets better!

1496
02:14:56,388 --> 02:14:57,456
Goodbye!

1497
02:15:11,637 --> 02:15:13,005
From De thrill.

1498
02:15:15,700 --> 02:15:17,042
What does he say?

1499
02:15:18,600 --> 02:15:19,500
Nothing.

1500
02:15:20,200 --> 02:15:21,780
Come on. Let me look.

1501
02:15:23,300 --> 02:15:24,300
Gosh!

1502
02:15:24,600 --> 02:15:26,200
He wants you to go to Hollywood.

1503
02:15:28,000 --> 02:15:29,200
Should I help you pack?

1504
02:15:31,000 --> 02:15:34,393
No. Let's go find
that room in Bloomsbury.

1505
02:15:37,900 --> 02:15:39,400
I think I'll take the cloth.

1506
02:15:40,500 --> 02:15:43,140
Like to bet on your first customers?
